{:proof/updated-at "2026-03-29T21:50:13.039248130Z", :proof/falsify-completed? true, :proof/cycles [{:cycle/id "apm-a01A09-C001", :cycle/blocker-id "root", :cycle/phase :completed, :cycle/phases-completed [:observe :propose :execute :validate :classify :integrate :commit :gate-review], :cycle/phase-data {:observe {:blocker-id "root", :notes "WHAT IS REALLY BEING ASKED: f in L^p([0,inf)) for some 1 < p < inf, and G(z) = integral_0^inf f(t) e^{tz} dt. Show G is analytic on the right half-plane Re(z) > 0, and find an additional condition making G entire. NOTE: The problem as stated has a likely sign issue — e^{tz} GROWS for Re(z) > 0 and t > 0, making the integral diverge for generic L^p functions. The intended formula is almost certainly the Laplace transform G(z) = integral f(t) e^{-tz} dt (with a minus sign), where e^{-tz} decays for Re(z) > 0. I solve the Laplace transform version.\n\nWHY IT IS HARD: The analyticity proof requires justifying differentiation under the integral sign (or Morera + Fubini). The dominated convergence argument needs Holder inequality to bound the integrand. Students often forget the Holder step. The 'entire' part requires understanding that compact support of f eliminates the exponential growth issue for all z."}, :propose {:approach "Holder inequality shows G converges absolutely for Re(z) > 0. Morera theorem + Fubini gives analyticity. Compact support makes G entire.", :notes "THE KEY INSIGHT: Holder gives |G(z)| <= ||f||_p * ||e^{-tz}||_q where 1/p+1/q=1. For Re(z) = x > 0: ||e^{-tx}||_q = (1/(qx))^{1/q} < inf. So G is well-defined. For analyticity, the cleanest approach is Morera: for any triangle gamma in the right half-plane, integral_gamma G(z) dz = integral_gamma integral_0^inf f(t)e^{-tz} dt dz = integral_0^inf f(t) integral_gamma e^{-tz} dz dt = 0 (by Fubini + the fact that z -> e^{-tz} is entire).\n\nTHE NAIVE APPROACH THAT FAILS: Try to show G has a power series expansion directly. This requires computing G^{(n)}(z_0) and showing the Taylor series converges, which is much harder than Morera. Also: trying to use the formula as written (e^{+tz}) without noticing the sign issue leads to a divergent integral."}, :execute {:artifacts ["proof-a01A09-inline"], :notes "THE CLEAN PROOF:\n\nConvention: I take G(z) = integral_0^inf f(t) e^{-tz} dt (Laplace transform).\n\nStep 1: Absolute convergence. For Re(z) = x > 0, by Holder with exponents p, q (1/p+1/q=1): integral_0^inf |f(t) e^{-tz}| dt = integral |f(t)| e^{-tx} dt <= ||f||_p (integral_0^inf e^{-qtx} dt)^{1/q} = ||f||_p (1/(qx))^{1/q} < inf. So G(z) is well-defined on the right half-plane. (This is routine but essential: the Holder step converts L^p integrability + exponential decay into absolute convergence.)\n\nStep 2: Analyticity via Morera. Let gamma be any closed triangle in {Re(z) > 0}. Then: integral_gamma G(z) dz = integral_gamma [integral_0^inf f(t) e^{-tz} dt] dz.\n\nBy Fubini (justified since integral_gamma integral |f(t) e^{-tz}| dt |dz| < inf, using Step 1 uniformly along gamma): = integral_0^inf f(t) [integral_gamma e^{-tz} dz] dt.\n\nFor each fixed t, z -> e^{-tz} is entire. By Cauchy's theorem: integral_gamma e^{-tz} dz = 0. Therefore integral_gamma G(z) dz = 0.\n\nBy Morera's theorem, G is analytic on {Re(z) > 0}. QED.\n\nStep 3: Entire extension. G is entire if the integral converges for ALL z in C. For Re(z) < 0, |e^{-tz}| = e^{-t Re(z)} = e^{t|Re(z)|} grows exponentially in t. The integral converges only if f decays fast enough. The additional assumption: f has compact support, i.e., there exists T > 0 such that f(t) = 0 for a.e. t > T. Then: G(z) = integral_0^T f(t) e^{-tz} dt. For any z: |G(z)| <= integral_0^T |f(t)| e^{T|Re(z)|} dt = e^{T|Re(z)|} ||f||_{L^1([0,T])} < inf. Analyticity follows by the same Morera argument. So G is entire."}, :validate {:validation-artifacts ["proof-a01A09-checked"], :notes "NON-CIRCULARITY: Uses (i) Holder inequality, (ii) Fubini, (iii) Cauchy theorem for entire functions, (iv) Morera theorem. All independent. The sign issue is noted — if the problem means e^{+tz}, the domain of analyticity would be Re(z) < 0 by the same argument. No Lean — Laplace transform and Morera theorem composition not in Mathlib. Design sketch: would need MeasureTheory.integral_parametric_holomorphic or similar."}, :classify {:classification :proved, :rationale "Complete proof of analyticity and identification of compact-support condition for entireness. Sign convention noted.", :notes "CONFIDENCE INVERSION: The L^p condition on f seems like a weak integrability condition, but combined with the exponential kernel it produces a function G that is ANALYTIC — infinitely differentiable with convergent Taylor series. The surprise: L^p data on the real line, fed through an integral transform, becomes analytic data in the complex plane. This is the power of the Laplace/Fourier transform: it trades regularity in one domain for decay in the transform domain, and vice versa. The Paley-Wiener theorem makes this precise."}, :integrate {:rationale "All parts proved.", :ledger-changes [], :notes "CONNECTIONS: (1) Paley-Wiener theorem: G entire of exponential type iff f has compact support. Our problem is the 'if' direction. (2) Laplace transform theory: the abscissa of convergence is determined by the growth of f. (3) The Holder step is the same technique as in Lp boundedness of integral operators (Schur test). (4) Morera + Fubini is a standard technique for proving analyticity of parameter-dependent integrals — appears in Gamma function, zeta function, and all special function theory.\n\nEXAM-DAY FIELD KIT: (1) Holder: integral |fg| <= ||f||_p ||g||_q. (2) e^{-xt} in L^q([0,inf)) iff x > 0, with ||e^{-xt}||_q = (1/(qx))^{1/q}. (3) Morera: integral over every triangle = 0 implies analytic. (4) Fubini swaps integral_z and integral_t when the double integral converges absolutely. (5) Compact support of f makes the Laplace transform entire."}, :commit {:saved? true}, :gate-review {:gates-passed true, :result-status :proved}}, :cycle/started-at "2026-03-29T21:51:28.620276632Z", :cycle/updated-at "2026-03-29T21:51:28.620600806Z", :cycle/result-status :proved}], :proof/ledger {"root" {:item/id "root", :item/label "Prove a01A09", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{}, :item/unlocks #{}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}}, :proof/active-license nil, :proof/current-mode :CONSTRUCT, :proof/problem-id "apm-a01A09", :proof/canonical {:statement "Suppose $f$ is a complex-valued function defined on $[0,\\infty)$ that\nbelongs to $L^p([0,\\infty))$ for some $p$ such that\n$1<p<\\infty$. Define $G$ on the right half-plane by\n$G(z)=\\int_0^{\\infty}f(t) e^{tz} dt$. Prove that $G(z)$ is analytic\nfor $z$ with $\\Re z>0$. What additional assumption would ensure that\n$f$ is entire?\n\n", :closure-criterion "All parts proved analytically", :statement-hash "e2d6792902f86d36994c7d601f66d0df6924a0878ba851eea0ae13323156f872", :version-history [{:version 0, :statement "Suppose $f$ is a complex-valued function defined on $[0,\\infty)$ that\nbelongs to $L^p([0,\\infty))$ for some $p$ such that\n$1<p<\\infty$. Define $G$ on the right half-plane by\n$G(z)=\\int_0^{\\infty}f(t) e^{tz} dt$. Prove that $G(z)$ is analytic\nfor $z$ with $\\Re z>0$. What additional assumption would ensure that\n$f$ is entire?\n\n", :hash "e2d6792902f86d36994c7d601f66d0df6924a0878ba851eea0ae13323156f872", :changed-at "2026-03-29T21:50:13.039248130Z", :reason "Initial load from APM archive"}]}, :proof/version 0, :proof/tryharder-log [], :proof/failed-routes []}